  section
    h2.bullet How webpack works
    hr
    ul
      li.bullet An external tool builds an AST of your code (like browserify).
      li.bullet Expanded API in your code to mark up dependencies (like require.js).
      li.bullet It generates one or more bundle files to include via script tags.

  section
    h2.bullet Best of both worlds
    hr
    ul
      li.bullet It is not nearly as configuration heavy to drive as browserify.
      li.bullet It does not require the severe changes that AMD forces onto your code.
      li.bullet It can load commonjs, AMD, UMD or Global code seamlessly.

  section
    h2.bullet It all starts with require()
    hr
    ul
      li.bullet Webpack extends the standard require function
        pre
          code.language-javascript.
            require('./slides');

      li.bullet With the ability to specify inline 'loaders' to use while processing.
        pre
          code.language-javascript.
            // Use coffee-loader to compile CS on the fly.
            require('coffee!./slides.coffee');

      li.bullet These can also be set up in a config file, so you don't have to modify your code.
        pre
          code.language-javascript.
            // webpack.config.js
            loaders: [ { test: /\.coffee/, loader: "coffee-loader" } ]

  section(data-bespoke-backdrop='plans')
    h2.bullet Webpack can bundle more than just javascript!
    hr

    pre
      code.language-javascript.
        require('style!css!less!./style.less')

    h3.bullet This includes :
    ul
      li.bullet CSS/SASS/Less.
      li.bullet HTML / templates.
      li.bullet Images and Fonts.

  section
    h2 How it bundles these is kind of surprising
    hr
    ul
      li.bullet You only need to include a single bundle.js file via a script tag.
      li.bullet Everything is transformed to javascript modules.
      li.bullet ie. requiring a css file will add a style tag to the head.
      li.bullet Smaller assets can be base64url encoded.
      li.bullet Larger assets get loaded as files on demand.
      li.bullet Files will be copied to the destination with a content hash as filename.

  section
    h2 This all means that
    hr
    ul
      li.bullet Fewer HTTP request needed to render a page.
      li.bullet Shorter loading times for end-users.
      li.bullet Hash based filename means you can effectively cache the assets.
      li.bullet Faster deploys, since you only need to upload new files.
      li.bullet You finally have a single pipeline for all your assets too.
      li.bullet This means grunt, gulp and yeoman become mostly unneccessary.

  section
    h2 The tooling is really great too!
    hr
    ul
      li.bullet There are loaders for everything.
      li.bullet They expand node's module resolution to everything.
      li.bullet The 'watch' mode just works.
      li.bullet Minification etc just requires you to use webpack -p
      li.bullet webpack-dev-server works great for testing SPA's
      li.bullet use webpack-dev-middleware if you have a server-side aspect.

